data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>()`. It validates the type **and** returns the typed instance, so you can keep asserting on it. Your current cast would throw `InvalidCastException` before the null check ever runs if the type is wrong.

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

The generic overload (MSTest v3+) returns the cast object, eliminating the separate cast and null check.
